s'; the principles of state environmental responsibility and liability within (and potentially beyond) the limits of national jurisdiction as an increasingly critical aspect of international law; and the right and duty of the state to take environmental measures in its capacity as 'custodian' for its own people and the world community. This persuasive and compelling study is of an issue of crucial importance, in international environmental law, or related subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEnvironmental law, International. 7aLAW / Environmental.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757988340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487579883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487579883.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK